(1, 'Origin of life', '', 'Maël and Raphaël', '2015-12-17', '    <p>What always amazed us in biology was the explanation even partial of the life’s origin.</p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n       <img src="images/curiosity.jpg"/>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    <p> In order to understand biological system I usually imagine a machine working the same way.</p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n       <img src="images/machine.jpg"/>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    <p>But until now, machines never were able to improve itself just like living being. What gives its ability to life being and is there only advantages ?</p>\r\n\r\n    <p> <strong> Problem: In what extent possessing undifferentiated <a href="stem_cells.php">stem cells</a> is good for healthy ? </strong> </p>\r\n\r\n    <p> <a href="anmimal_regeneration.php" alt="A young man watching a plant growing"> How much animals are able to fix themselves ?</a><br/></p>\r\n        \r\n    <p><a href="Knock_out_mice.php" alt="wheels making work a human body">  Is it possible to use stem cells for the research ?</a> <br/></p>\r\n\r\n    <p><a href="human_regeneration.php"> Can we control theses fixings ?</a> \r\n<?php include("comentslp.php"); ?>\r\n</p>\r\n<br/><br/><br/>', '', '', 'english'),
(2, 'Regeneration in animals', '', 'Maël and Raphaël', '2015-12-17', '    	<p>All animals are able to regenerate, but on different levels. After a modest injury (a bruise or a skin wound), you would expect your body to nearly completely repair the damaged tissue over a period one or two weeks : that’s regeneration. But a severe injury, like the loss of an arm, you normally wouldn’t expect much of your regenerative capacities, we accept that the arm is lost forever and look for engineers that produce an artificial device, a prosthesis, to replace the missing body part. The situation is quite different, and much more promising, for salamanders and planarian flatworms that have incredible regeneration skills. Below we will describe how they do it. This information may be helpful in determining how the regeneration process could be manipulated in humans.</p>\r\n	<br/>\r\n    	<p><strong>Problem: To what extent animals as planarian and salamanders are able to regenerate themselves ?</strong/></p>\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n    			<h3>Generation of body parts in planarian flatworms</h3>\r\n    \r\n\r\n    	<p>Planarians are invertebrate flatworms that have the unbelievable ability to regenerate any part of their body. The most extraordinary example is the full regeneration of head structures after decapitation of the animal. More surprisingly, as a cherry on the cake, the animal also regains its memory.</p>\r\n    \r\n	<p>The experience begin with an <span id="amputation">amputation</span>, in this picture decapitation, it is the first step of the process in order to understand mechanisms of planarian regeneration. Indeed we will see how planaria’s body reacts.</p>\r\n	<p>The accumulation of stem cells on the site of the injury forms what we call a <span id="blastema">blastema</span>. It is this cluster of cells that will reproduce, regenerate, the missing body part.</p>\r\n	<p>Stem cells of the blastema receive different kind of signals from nerve cells, provided by hormones. The same neurotransmitter is required in both processes but in order to <span id="regeneration_control">differentiate or to proliferate</span> different hormones are used. The one shown on the picture in blue induce an increase in the number of stem cells wheras the one in red order to the stem cell what lineage to adopt (turning into muscle, vasculature, nerve, epithelium, connective tissue, or others): what precursor cells to become. There are many different hormones such as serotonin and dopamine, some of them are produced by muscle cells.</p>\r\n    	<figure>\r\n    		<img src="images/planeria2.00.jpg" alt="hormone''s action" title="Reference: Tal Shomrat and Michael Levin, Tufts University ; Francesc Cebria, University of Barcelona"/>\r\n    	<figcaption>Figure 4: neurotransmitters (black, blue and red circles) from nerve cells (nc) instruct either to increase stem cells (sc) proliferation or differentiation into precusor cells (pc)</figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n\r\n    \r\n	<p>As a conclusion, the functioning of planarian regeneration can be recaped in this diagram.</p>\r\n    	<figure>\r\n    		<img src="images/conclusion.jpg"/>\r\n    	</figure>\r\n\r\n	<p>So, planarian flatworms seems to have a complete ability to regenerate themselves, even the head, but what about salamanders, can they regain memory as planarian ?</p>\r\n\r\n    			<h3>Regeneration of body parts in salamanders</h3>\r\n    \r\n	<p> Another exemple of animal with extraordinary regeneration capacity is the salamander. Salamender doesn''t regenerate their all body from a head like flatworms, but they can regenerate a member after an amputation.<p>\r\n    	<video src="videos/Cell regeneration in the salamander.mp4" controls poster="videos/salamander.jpg" max-width="100%" min-width="100%" title="References: Nadia Rosenthal" preload="metadata"></video>\r\n    <p> After an injury (partial or total loss of body structures) different process repair the injured zone, partially or totally.</p>\r\n\r\n    				<h4 id="inflammatory">Inflammatory response</h4>\r\n    	<p> The process begins with the inflammatory response where blood vessels dilate, allowing more blood to enter the injured zone. This in turn leads to an enhanced presence of white blood cells, neutrophils and lymphocytes, that enter the tissue and initiate the process of immune defense and tissue repair (figure 1). The ensuing inflammation is also responsable for the pain sensation, because macrophages produce chemical messengers that stimulate nociceptive nerves.</p>\r\n    	<figure>\r\n    		<img src="images/inflamation.jpg" alt="vasodilatation" title=""/>\r\n    		<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n    	<p>Both innate and adapted immunity leads to elimination of micro-organism that have entered the wound.</p>\r\n    <h4 id="unknown">Stem cells recruitment</h4>\r\n    <p>The injury also causes the recruitment of Stem Cells, who are essential for the regeneration of the tissues.The mechanism responsible of Stem cell’s recruitment, globally referred to as the “injury signal” isn’t known yet, but may cytokines produced by the macrophages may play an important role (acting as chemo-attractants). </p>\r\n<p><a href="#" id="toggler">For more informations</a>\r\n<div id="toggle">\r\nIndeed, a studie performed by the Australian Regenerative Medecine Institute shows that the macrophages play a role in the regeneration of members for salamenders : they found that salamanders with macrophages being recruited into the injuried zone normally regenerate a new member in about one yearwhereas those that fail to recruit macrophages take much more longer to fully recover. Salamanders totally lacking macrophages do not regenerate at all; these animals just manage to heal the wound by covering the body part with a scar tissue.<p></div>\r\n\r\n\r\n    <figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/salamanderr.jpg" alt="salamender regeneration" title="Reference: Georgia Tech University"/>\r\n    	<figcaption>Figure 2: regeneration of a Salamander’s limb after an amputation</figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n\r\n    <h3>Summary</h3>\r\n    \r\n\r\n    <p> After an <a href="#amputation">amputation</a>, through a <a href="#unknown"> process still to be elucidated</a> but involving infiltrated <a href="#inflammatory"> macrophages</a>, stem cells are attracted to the site of the injury. They form stem cells <a href="#blastema">cluster</a> which, through <a href="#regeneration_control">control by locally generated hormones</a>, will differentiate into the different missing organs</p>\r\n\r\n    <h3>References</h3>\r\n    <ul>\r\n    	<li>Alan H. CRUICKSHANK, André PARAF, Catherine ZILLER,<a href="http://www.universalis-edu.com/encyclopedie/regeneration-et-cicatrisation/"> « RÉGÉNÉRATION ET CICATRISATION »</a>, Encyclopædia Universalis [en ligne], consulté le 17 décembre 2015.URL</li>\r\n    	<li>Par R. FRANQUINET,<a href="references/serotonin.pdf"> « Role de la serotonine et des catecholamines dans la regeneration de la planaire Polycelis tenuis » </a>,1979</li>\r\n    	<li>Jessica N. Witchley, Mirjam Mayer Daniel E. Wagner Jared H. Owen and Peter W. Reddien, <a href="references/hormons.pdf">« Muscle Cells Provide Instructions for Planarian Regeneration »</a>, August 15, 2013</li>\r\n    	<li>Francesc Cebrià, <a href="references/transmeteurs.pdf">« Regenerating the central nervous system: How easy for planarians! »</a>, January 2008</li>\r\n    	<li>Tal Shomrat, and Michael Levin, <a href="references/planeria_head.pdf">« An Automated Training Paradigm Reveals Long-term Memory in Planaria and Its Persistence Through Head Regeneration »</a>, 2013.</li>\r\n<li>Brian Merchant <a href="http://motherboard.vice.com/blog/australian-scientists-think-salamander-like-human-limb-regeneration-is-possible">« Australian Scientists Think "Salamander-Like" Human Limb Regeneration Is Possible »</a>, 2013.</li>\r\n<li>Nadia Rosenthal <a href="http://www.hhmi.org/biointeractive/newt-limb-regeneration">« Potent Biology: St\r\nem Cells, Cloning, and Regeneration, Newt limb regeneration »</a>, 2006.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n\r\n<script>\r\n/* <![CDATA[ */ \r\n/*\r\n|-----------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n|  jQuery Toggle Script by Matt - skyminds.net\r\n|-----------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n|\r\n| Affiche/cache le contenu d''un bloc une fois qu''un lien est cliqué.\r\n|\r\n*/\r\n\r\n// On attend que la page soit chargée \r\njQuery(document).ready(function()\r\n{\r\n   // On cache la zone de texte\r\n   jQuery(''#toggle'').hide();\r\n   // toggle() lorsque le lien avec l''ID #toggler est cliqué\r\n   jQuery(''a#toggler'').click(function()\r\n  {\r\n      jQuery(''#toggle'').toggle(400);\r\n      return false;\r\n   });\r\n});\r\n/* ]]> */ \r\n</script>', '', '', 'english'),
(3, 'Stem cells definition', '', 'Maël and Raphaël', '2016-05-04', '    <h3>Summary</h3>\r\n    \r\n    <p> Stem cells are able to replicate themselves into <a href="#self_renewal">identical cells</a>, but they also can <a href="#differentiation">differentiate </a> into one or several  tissues according to their types and the environment. Indeed the diffrence between stem cells and differentiated ones is the ability of multiple divisions.</p>\r\n    <h3 id="different_types"> Different types </h3>\r\n\r\n<p>There is differents types of stem cells, corresponding to different states of différentiation.</p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/different_types.png" title=""/>\r\n    	<figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n<h4>Totipotent</h4>\r\n<p>Totipotent cells are able to différenciate in every type of cell, and to create a full organism. But they can''t renew indefinetly, a culture of totipotent cells will turn into a pluripotent cells culture after a few mitoses, that''s why totipotent cells are not really stem cells.\r\nthe first cells of an embryo are totipotent cells.</p>\r\n<h4>Pluripotent cells</h4>\r\n<p>Pluripotent cells are able to differenciate in almost every type of cells, without some specifics embryonic cells ( placenta cells ), so pluripotent cells can''t create a full organism like totipotent cells.</p>\r\n<h4>Multipotent cells</h4>\r\n<p>Pluripotent cells are able to differenciate in differents cells, but cells with commun caracteristics ( blood cells, cells specifics to an organ ...).\r\nMultipotent cells are more specialised and specifics than pluripotent cells, and generaly, a type of multipotent stem cell is associated to an organ or a part of the body.</p>\r\n<h4>Unipotent cells</h4>\r\n<p>Unipotent stem cells are able to replicate and renew indefinitly, but they can only differenciate into one specific cell, unipotent cells renew a specific population of cells. unipotent cells are the last differentiation step, before the final cell.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h3 id="self_renewal"> Self renewal </h3>\r\n    <h4>Telomerase</h4>\r\n    \r\n    <p>Actually at each division, there is a loss of a small part at the end of the chromosome, it is called the <a href="before_replication">telomere </a>. And stem cells replicates many times in their all life, indeed they need an enzyme that rebulid this telomere, this one is named telomerase.</p>\r\n    \r\n    <h5 id="before_replication">Before replication</h4>\r\n    <p>On this picture, both situation are represented : when there is effective telomerase and telomere is rebuilt on the left and when there isn''t telomerase and in this case chromosome is shorter.<p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/telomerase1.png" title=""/>\r\n    	<figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    <h5 id="positioning_telomerase">Positioning of telomerase</h4>\r\n    <p>Before intervention of telomerase the chromosome of the daughter cell is shorter than the mother''s one. Then the telomerase comes with its strand of RNA.</p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/telomerase2.png" title=""/>\r\n    	<figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    <h5 id="DNA_polymerase">DNA polymerase</h4>\r\n      <p>Then de DNA polymerase complete the chromosome strand with complementary nucleotides with the telomere RNA strand.<p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/telomerase4.png" alt=""/>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    <h4 href="niches"> Niches </h4>\r\nA niche is a local tissue, a kind of microenvironments, where stem cells are maintained and fed but also regulated and, when needed, differentiated.\r\n    <figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/niches1.png" alt=""/>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n	<h5> Stem cells maintain </h3>\r\n<p>In the basis of the intestinal gland, there is expression of Wnt in order to make proliferate multipotent stem cells and diffrenciation. But BMP-4 is also expressed, in order to regulate the differenciation because cells there are not  supposed to differentiate  to much.<p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/niches2.png" alt=""/>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n	<h5 id="differentiation">Differentiation </h5>\r\n<p> The low expression of WNT in the middle and high region allow NOTCH to differentiate stem cells into differentiated cells.</p>\r\n    <h3>Differentiation</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>\r\n<br/>Stem cells are undiferenciated cells, able to replicate and renew indefinetly, and to differenciate into a specialised cell .\r\nGeneraly, the mitosis of a stem cell create one other stem cell and one progenetive cell who''s going to differenciate into a specialised cell. So the stem cell''s number remain constant.<p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n    	<img src="" alt=""/>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n<p>In normal time, stem cells doesn''t replicate much, just enough in order to keep the cell''s population constant. But, after an injury, stem cells are activated (by the unknow "injury signal") and start replicate verry fast, in order to provide enough cells to fix the injury. that''s why stem cell''s are verry important for regeneration.</p>\r\n    <h3>References</h3>\r\n    <ul>\r\n    	<li>Bipasha Bose, "Past, present and future of Stem Cells in Regenerative Medicine, after 2011</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <ul>\r\n    	<li>Camille Bismuth, "Les cellules souches chez l’adulte. Applications possibles en medecine veterinaire", 2008</li>\r\n    </ul>', '', '', 'english'),
(4, 'Origine de la vie', '', 'Maël et Raphaël', '2015-12-17', '    	<p>Dans la biologie, on a toujours été émerveillé par l''explication même partielle de l''origine de la vie.</p>\r\n        <figure>\r\n    	   <img src="images/curiosity.jpg"/>\r\n        </figure>\r\n    	<p> Dans le but de comprendre les systèmes biologiques, nous nous imaginions qu''ils fonctionnaient comme une machine.</p>\r\n        <figure>\r\n    	   <img src="images/machine.jpg"/>\r\n    	</figure>\r\n    	<p>Mais jusqu''à maintenant aucune machine n''a été capable de s''auto améliorer ou de se réparer. Quel élément donne aux êtres vivants cette capacité ?</p>\r\n\r\n    	<p> <strong> Problématique: dans quelle mesure posséder plus de <a href="stem_cells.php">cellules souches</a> est-il bon pour la santé ? </strong> </p>\r\n\r\n    	<p> <a href="anmimal_regeneration_fr.html" alt="A young man watching a plant growing"> Dans quelle mesure les animaux sont-ils capables de se régénérer par eux-même ?</a><br/></p>\r\n		\r\n        <p><a href="dangerous_regeneration_fr.html" alt=""> Dans quelle mesure posséder cette capacité a-t-il un mauvais coté ?</a> <br/></p>\r\n\r\n		<p><a href="human_regeneration_fr.html"> Est-il possible de controler ces régénérations?</a> </p>\r\n        <br/><br/><br/>', '', '', 'french'),
(5, 'Régénération animale', '', 'Maël et Raphaël', '2015-12-17', '    <p>Tous les animaux sont capables de se régénérer, mais à des niveaux différents. Si on se fait une coupure, on pourra espérer guérir en quelques jours : cela s''appelle la régénération. Mais si on est amputé d''un bras, par exemple, on ne pourra espérer en voir un nouveau pousser, la régénération humaine est donc limitée. En revanche pour des animaux comme les planaires ou certaines salamandres cela est possible.</p>\r\n    <p><strong>Problématique: Dans quelle mesure les animaux sont-ils capable de se régénérer ?</strong/></p>\r\n    \r\n    <h3>Résumé</h3>\r\n    \r\n\r\n    <p> Après une <a href="#amputation">amputation</a>, au travers d''un <a href="#unknown"> mécanisme que l''on ne connait pas encore</a> mais utilisant probablement des <a href="#inflammatory"> macrophages</a>, les cellules souches sont attirées sur le lieu de la blessure. Elles forment, une sorte <a href="#blastema">d''amas</a> qui, controlé par des <a href="#regeneration_control">hormones produite dans cette région de l''organisme</a>, vont se différencier dans les différents organes manquant</p>\r\n\r\n    <h3>Régénération de parties du corps chez les vers aquatiques dénommés planaires</h3>\r\n    \r\n\r\n    <p>Les planaires sont de petits vers aquatiques qui ont l''incroyable capacité de régénérer n''importe quelle partie de leur corps. L''exemple le plus extraordianire est l''entière régénération de leurs après décapitation. Encore plus surprenant, la cerise sur le gateau, l''animal recouvre sa mémoire.</p>   \r\n    <h4 id="amputation">Amputation</h4>\r\n    <figure>\r\n        <img src="images/planeria.jpg" title="Reference:  Tal Shomrat and Michael Levin, Tufts University"/>\r\n        <figcaption>Figure 3 : Amputation, dans cette exemple décapitation, est la première étape pour comprendre le mécanisme de régénération chez les planaires. Ainsi, nous découvrirons comment réagit le planaire à cette blessure</figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    <h4 id="blastema">Blastème</h4>\r\n    <p>L''accumalation des cellules souches sur le lieux de la blessure forment ce que l''on appelle un blastème. Les cellules souches composant cet amas vont régénérés les parties du corps manquant.</p>\r\n    <h4 id="regeneration_control">Contrôl de la régénération</h4>\r\n    <figure>\r\n        <img src="images/control.jpg" alt="hormone''s action" title="Reference: Francesc Cebria, University of Barcelona"/>\r\n        <figcaption>Figure 4: signal qui ordonnent aux cellules souches en quels type de cellues se différencier.</figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    <p>Les cellules souches peuvent recevoir différents types de messages, véhiculés par des hormones. Ces dernières indiquent où, quand et en quel types (muscles, celules vasculaire, nerveuses et autres) les cellules souches doivent proliférer. Il y a plein d''hormones qui participent à ces mécanismes, la dopamine et la sérotonine sont l''unes d''elles, certaines d''entre-elles sont synthétisées dans les muscles.<p>\r\n    \r\n    <h4>Conclusion</h4>\r\n    <figure>\r\n        <img src="images/conclusion.jpg"/>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    \r\n    <h3>Régénération de membres entiers chez la salamandre</h3>\r\n    \r\n\r\n    <p> Après une blessure (partielle ou totale) différents mécanismes soignent la zone endomagée.</p>\r\n\r\n    <h4 id="inflammatory">Réponse inflamatoire</h4>\r\n    <p> Les vaisseaux sanguins se dilatent pour permettre à plus de sang d''enterer sur la zone de la blessure. Ainsi, la quantité de globule blanc, neutrophiles et lymphocytes dans ces tissus augmentent. Et se faisant, ces cellules initient le mécanismes de défense immunitaire et de réparation des tissus (figure 1). Il s''en suit une inflamation responsable de la sensation de douleur, les macrophages (appartient au groupe des globules blancs) produisent en effet des messagers chimiques qui stimulent des nerfs appelés nocicepteurs.</p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n        <img src="images/vasodilatation.jpg" alt="vasodilatation" title=""/>\r\n        <figcaption></figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    <p>Les deux types d''immunité innée ou acquise mènent toutes deux à l''élimination de micro-organismes entrés sur les lieux de la blessure.</p>\r\n    <h4 id="unknown">Recrutement des cellules souches</h4>\r\n    <p>La blessure engendre égaleemnt le recrutement de cellules souches, qui sont essentielles pour la régénération des tissus.</p>\r\n    <p>Le mécanisme responsable du rectrutement des cellules souches, que l''on pourrait appeler "signal de blessure", mais celui-ci n''est pas encore connu. Mais les cytokines produites par des macrophages jouent certainenement un grand rôle. Par exmple, une étude menée en Australie, par l''Australian Regenerative Medecine Institute sur des salamandres, des animaux connus pour leur grande capacité de régénération a montré que le recrutement de macrophages avait un impact sur celle-ci.</p>\r\n    <p>Une salamandre avec des macrophages en quantité normale régénère un membre amputé en à peu près un ans. Celles qui ne réussissent pas a recruter des macrophages sur la zone de la blessure, se régénère en beaucoup plus temps. Et celles, qui n''en ont pas du tout ne se régénère tout simplement pas, ces dernières ne peuvent que recouvrir les lieux de l''amputation par des cicatrices.</p>\r\n    <figure>\r\n        <img src="images/salamender.jpg" alt="salamender regeneration" title=""/>\r\n        <figcaption>Figure 2: régénération de la patte d''une salamandre après une amputation</figcaption>\r\n    </figure>\r\n    <h3>Sources</h3>\r\n    <ul>\r\n        <li>Alan H. CRUICKSHANK, André PARAF, Catherine ZILLER,<a href="http://www.universalis-edu.com/encyclopedie/regeneration-et-cicatrisation/"> « RÉGÉNÉRATION ET CICATRISATION »</a>, Encyclopædia Universalis [en ligne], consulté le 17 décembre 2015.URL</li>\r\n        <li>Par R. FRANQUINET,<a href="references/serotonin.pdf"> « Role de la serotonine et des catecholamines dans la regeneration de la planaire Polycelis tenuis » </a>,1979</li>\r\n        <li>Jessica N. Witchley, Mirjam Mayer Daniel E. Wagner Jared H. Owen and Peter W. Reddien, <a href="references/hormons.pdf">« Muscle Cells Provide Instructions for Planarian Regeneration</a>, August 15, 2013</li>\r\n        <li>Francesc Cebrià, <a href="references/transmeteurs.pdf">« Regenerating the central nervous system: How easy for planarians! »</a>, January 2008</li>\r\n        <li>Tal Shomrat, and Michael Levin, <a href="references/planeria_head.pdf">« An Automated Training Paradigm Reveals Long-term Memory in Planaria and Its Persistence Through Head Regeneration</a>, 2013.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n    <br/><br/>  ', '', '', 'french'),
(6, 'Knock out Mice', '', 'Alexandre Karnat, Narcisa Girigan, Raphaël Garnaud', '2017-01-15', '<p>There are twenty one thousand genes in the human genome, but we dont’ know yet for what protein each gene code for. It is just like if you have inherited from your grandfather a scrapyard and you don’t know the use of each car pieces.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Indeed, geneticians needs a method to make a link between genes and protein. To do so, we can use the aphorism : the value of something is revealed when it doesn’t exist any more. In the comparison  with the scrapyard, the idea is to remove a piece of a car (deactivate a gene). Then you start it and look for differences in the car behaviour (phenotype). Indeed, throughout the mechanical knowledge, it is possible to determine the function of this piece in the car (for what protein does the gene code for).</p>\r\n</br>\r\n<h4>Creation of the targeting vector</h4>\r\n<img style="width:5%;float: left;" src="images/tube.jpg"/>\r\n<p>The targeting vector is a DNA sequence composed of two parts. A selection marker gene that will take the place of the targeted gene. This one is surrounded by the immediate neighbour sequences of the targeted gene.</p>\r\n<figure>\r\n	<center><img src="images/schema.png" alt="" title="Reference:"/></center>\r\n<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n</figure>\r\n<p>Sometimes, instead of the selection marker, only a damaged version of the original targeted gene is used. But it is easier to use the selection marker gene, as its name implies, to obtain only the cells with the selection marker (this will be seen in more detail in <a href="#neg"> the negative selection part </a>). The  necessity to use the neighbour sequences of the targeted gene will be explained <a href="#w">later</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Introduction of the targeting vector</h4>\r\n<img style="width:5%;float: left;" src="images/elec.jpg"/>\r\n<p>The objective is to introduce the targeting vector inside a group of cells, to do so, geneticists use a special phenomenon called electroporation. An electric fields is applied to the membrane of the cells surrounded by a saline solution. The permeability of the membrane increase and let the targeting vector come in.</p>\r\n<figure>\r\n	<center><img src="images/electroporation.png" alt="" title="Reference:"/></center>\r\n<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n</figure>\r\n<p>The membrane of the cells are composed of phospholipids with a head hydrophile and a tail hydrophob, indeed phospholipids are oriented tail to tail a make a bilayer (a). The electric field allow few water molecules to penetrate the bilayer, forming a water wire (b). The phospholipids next to the water wire reorient themselves toward the wire and allow more water and the targeting vector to enter (c).</p>\r\n<p>The atoms of the lipid head groups and tails are shown in orange and gray, respectively; water molecules in cyan; sodium ions in green; and chloride ions in pink.</p>\r\n<h4 id="w">What strategies can be used to inactivate genes?</h4>\r\n<br/>\r\n<p>There are two known methods: gene targeting, based on homologous recombination, and gene trapping, based on random integration.</p>\r\n    	<figure>\r\n    		<center><img src="images/1.gif" alt="" title="Reference:"/></center>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n<p>In this article, we will focus on the first one. The vector used in gene targeting contains an artificial DNA sequence which will inactivate a specific gene. Being able to choose the gene we’re about to knock out means knowing the DNA sequence of the host. The integration of the vector is possible thanks to Cre recombinase. This enzyme is a member of the integrase family and is linked to the artificial DNA, allowing it to insert itself in the natural DNA sequence, so, in the targeted gene. During homologous recombination, a process similar to meiosis, crossing-overs may happen, resulting in the sole insertion of the artificial DNA sequence. The gene is now inactivated because it can’t be transcripted anymore.</p>\r\n<br/>\r\n    	<figure>\r\n    		<center><img src="images/2.png" alt="" title="Reference:"/></center>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n<p>In what concerns gene trapping, the artificial DNA sequence is randomly integrated in the host’s DNA and will inactivate one of the genes because the generated RNA will not be translated anymore.</p>\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n<h4 id="neg">Positive selection</h4>\r\n<img style="width:5%;float: left;" src="images/petri-dish.png"/>\r\n    	<center><video src="videos/selection_marker.mp4" controls poster="videos/selection.png" width="500" title="References: Kristin Klucevsek, Ph.D." preload="metadata"></video>\r\n<figcaption>The complete video is available <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iVY-UkiYfzY">here</a></figcaption>\r\n</center>\r\n</br>\r\n<p>In the cell studied, the targeted gene has been replaced by a selection marker, this new gene can code for a  protein resistance to antibiotic. In order to obtain only cells knocked out, we can make grow the cell in a Petri dish, and then spread antibiotic. The only cells that remain will be the one carrying the selection marker gene because the others were killed by the antibiotic.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>Ups and downs</strong></h4>\r\n<br/>\r\n<center><table>\r\n   <caption></caption>\r\n\r\n   <thead> <!-- En-tête du tableau -->\r\n       <tr>\r\n           <th>Generally speaking</th>\r\n           <th>Gene targeting</th>\r\n           <th>Gene trapping</th>\r\n       </tr>\r\n   </thead>\r\n\r\n   <tbody> <!-- Corps du tableau -->\r\n       <tr>\r\n           <td>15% of gene knockouts are developmentally lethal, meaning that embryos can’t grow into adult mice</td>\r\n           <td>The DNA sequence of the targeted gene is known => accurate, high rate efficiency</td>\r\n           <td>Knocking out a random gene => no need of knowing DNA sequences</td>\r\n       </tr>\r\n       <tr>\r\n           <td>In some cases, the studied gene may have a different function in adults than in embryos</td>\r\n           <td>One specific vector can replace one targeted gene</td>\r\n           <td>One single vector could inactivate a variety of genes => less specific than gene targeting</td>\r\n       </tr>\r\n       <tr>\r\n           <td>Stem cells can be used to create knockout mice up to 10 years after being harvested</td>\r\n           <td></td>\r\n           <td>Since this is a random process, some genes may never be knocked out => less efficient than gene targeting</td>\r\n       </tr>\r\n   </tbody>\r\n</table></center>\r\n<br/>\r\n<h4>How to produce a useful offspring ?</strong></h4>\r\n<br/>\r\n    	<figure>\r\n    		<center><img src="images/3.gif" alt="" title="Reference:"/></center>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n\r\n<p>As showed in the picture above, previously modified stem cells (containing KO genes) are injected into blastocysts (with A genes) and after that the whole system is implanted into female mice (with A genes). The mice pups of the progeny will be chimeras, meaning that some of their cells contain KO genes (in red on the drawing) and some of them don’t (in yellow). During growth, embryonic stem cells can develop in any cellular type. Therefore, the adult chimeras will have two kinds of tissue: normal and knockout.</p>\r\n<p>A chimeric mouse produces 2 types of gametes: containing the KO gene or the A gene. Our objective is to obtain homozygote knockout mice (KO/KO). To do so, we have to cross a chimera with a normal, homozygote mouse containing the recessive gene A. (KO/A) and (KO/KO) genotypes have to have visible effects.</p>\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n<ol> \r\n\r\n<li>Chimera''s genotype : (A/A)+(KO/A). It produces : (A) or (KO) gametes.</br>For example if the chiemra contains 40% of (KO/A), we will have 20% of gametes carrying the mutaion (KO).</li>\r\n<li>Chimera X Mouse</br>The normal mouse has an (A/A) genotype.</br>\r\n<center><table>\r\n   <caption></caption>\r\n\r\n   <tbody> <!-- Corps du tableau -->\r\n       <tr>\r\n           <td>Gametes of the Mouse/Gametes of the Chimera</td>\r\n           <td>(A)</td>\r\n           <td>(KO)</td>\r\n       </tr>\r\n       <tr>\r\n           <td>(A)</td>\r\n           <td>(A/A)</td>\r\n	   <td>(A/KO)</td>\r\n       </tr>\r\n   </tbody>\r\n</table></center>\r\n\r\n</li>\r\n<li> (A/KO)X(A/KO)\r\n\r\n<center><table>\r\n   <caption></caption>\r\n\r\n   <tbody> <!-- Corps du tableau -->\r\n       <tr>\r\n           <td>Gametes of the first/Gametes of the second</td>\r\n           <td>(A)</td>\r\n           <td>(KO)</td>\r\n       </tr>\r\n       <tr>\r\n           <td>(A)</td>\r\n           <td>(A/A)</td>\r\n	   <td>(A/KO)</td>\r\n       </tr>\r\n       <tr>\r\n           <td>(KO)</td>\r\n           <td>(A/KO)</td>\r\n	   <td>(KO/KO)</td>\r\n       </tr>\r\n   </tbody>\r\n</table></center></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br/>\r\n<p>If we never obtain a (KO/KO) mouse, it may be because this genotype is lethal.</p>\r\n<p>The result of this process is the creation of knockout mice, which are homozygote with a (KO/KO) genotype.</p>\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n<h4>What are knockout mice used for ?</h4>\r\n<br/>\r\n<p>They provide useful information on the activity of the targeted gene, which will be interpreted by scientists and will finally help to better understand human diseases (ex: obesity).</p>\r\n    	<figure>\r\n    		<center><img src="images/4.jpg" alt="" title="Reference:"/></center>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n\r\n<p>The mouse at the right is normal and the one at the left is a knockout mouse. The second one is called Obese mouse because it has on a knocked out gene the ob/ob mutation. The result is that leptin, a hormone that says to your brain when you’re not hungry anymore, can’t be synthetized by the organism. Therefore, the mouse can’t stop eating and becomes obese. The effects of this mutation can be seen only when the mice are all grown up and become larger and larger.<p/>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h4>References</h4>\r\n    <ul>\r\n    	<li>Drs Mario R. Capecchi, Martin J. Evans and Oliver Smithies <a href="http://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/2007/advanced.html">Gene modification in Mice</a>,2007</li>\r\n    	<li>Martin L. Yarmush, Alexander Golberg,\r\nGregor Serša, Tadej Kotnik, and Damijan Miklav?i? <a href="http://lbk.fe.uni-lj.si/pdfs/arbe2014.pdf">« Electroporation-Based Technologies for Medicine: Principles, Applications, and Challenges »</a>, May 27, 2014</li>\r\n    	<li>Ron Milo and Rob Philips, « Cell Biology by the numbers », July 2015</li>\r\n    	<li>Joseph A.Majzoub, M.D., and Louis J.Muglia, M.D., Ph.D. <a href="http://web.mit.edu/hst.160/www/Knockout.pdf">«Molecular Medicine\r\nKnockOut Mice»</a>, April 4,  1996</li>\r\n    	<li><a href="http://www.animalresearch.info/en/designing-research/research-animals/mouse-gm/">«Mouse (GM)»</a></li>\r\n    	<li><a href="https://www.genome.gov/12514551/">«Knockout Mice»</a>, August 27, 2015</li>\r\n    	<li>Robert HU, Hannah Park, Victor Tan<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oLPjiwM0G7A">«Cre-LoxP Recombinase»</a>, August 27, 2015</li>\r\n    	<li>Kristin Klucevsek, Ph.D.<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iVY-UkiYfzY"> «Steps of knockout mouse»</a></li>\r\n    	<li><a href="http://www.wikiwand.com/en/Ob/ob_mouse">«ob/ob mouse»</a></li>\r\n	</ul>', '', '', 'english'),
(7, 'article 2', '', 'raphaël', '0000-00-00', '<p>There are twenty one thousand genes in the human genome, but we dont’ know yet for what protein each gene code for. It is just like if you have inherited from your grandfather a scrapyard and you don’t know the use of each car pieces.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Indeed, geneticians needs a method to make a link between genes and protein. To do so, we can use the aphorism : the value of something is revealed when it doesn’t exist any more. In the comparison  with the scrapyard, the idea is to remove a piece of a car (deactivate a gene). Then you start it and look for differences in the car behaviour (phenotype). Indeed, throughout the mechanical knowledge, it is possible to determine the function of this piece in the car (for what protein does the gene code for).</p>\r\n</br>\r\n<h4>Creation of the targeting vector</h4>\r\n<p>The targeting vector is a DNA sequence composed of two parts. A selection marker gene that will take the place of the targeted gene. This one is surrounded by the immediate neighbour sequences of the targeted gene.</p>\r\n<p>Sometimes, instead of the selection marker, only a damaged version of the original targeted gene is used. But it is easier to use the selection marker gene, as its name implies, to obtain only the cells with the selection marker (this will be seen in more detail in the negative selection part). The  necessity to use the neighbour sequences of the targeted gene will be explained later (What).</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Introduction of the targeting vector</h4>\r\n<p>The objective is to introduce the targeting vector inside the cell, to do so, geneticists use a special phenomenon called electroporation. An electric fields is applied to the membrane of the cell surrounded by a saline solution. The permeability of the membrane increase and let the targeting vector come in.</p>\r\n<figure>\r\n	<img src="images/electroporation.png" alt="" title="Reference:"/>\r\n<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n</figure>\r\n<p>The membrane of the cell is composed of phospholipids with a head hydrophile and a tail hydrophob, indeed phospholipids are oriented tail to tail a make a bilayer. The electric field allow few water molecules to penetrate the bilayer, forming a water wire. The phospholipids next to the water wire reorient themselves toward the wire and allow more water and the targeting vector to enter.</p>\r\n<p>The atoms of the lipid head groups and tails are shown in orange and gray, respectively; water molecules in cyan; sodium ions in green; and chloride ions in pink.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>Positive negative selection</h4>\r\n    	<video src="videos/selection_marker.mp4" controls poster="videos/selection.png" width="500" title="References: Nadia Rosenthal" preload="metadata"></video>\r\n\r\n<p>In the cell studied, the targeted gene has been replaced by a selection marker, this new gene can code for a  protein resistance to antibiotic. In order to obtain only cells knocked out, we can make grow the cell in a Petri dish, and then spread antibiotic. The only cells that remain will be the one carrying the selection marker gene because the others were killed by the antibiotic.</p>', '', '', 'english');
INSERT INTO `contenu` (`id`, `nom`, `categories`, `auteur`, `date`, `articles`, `mots_clees`, `adresse`, `language`) VALUES
(8, 'Induced Pluripotent Stem Cells', '', 'Nicolas Paiement, Narcisa Girigan, Alexandre Karnat, Garnaud Raphaël', '2017-04-13', '    <p>Over time, the number of stem cells in our body decrease. Actually, the only real cell able to differentiate into anyone is the zygote, just after the fertilization. So is this a fatality, does the cells begin as a zygote and then differentiate into specialized cells and never do the other way around ?</p>\r\n<p>Actually in 2012, Shinya Yamanaka discovered how to reverse the process. We can compare the DNA with a cooking book and on each page there would be a recipe of the type of cell. For example, a page can tell to the cell what protein synthesized to act like a skin cell. So the idea would be to turn the page until we get the recipe of embryonic stem cell, it is what he did using four different factors.</p>\r\n<br/>\r\n    <p><strong>Problem: how do we create scientifically Induced Pluripotent Stem Cells, what do we use them for and finally is there ethical issues ?</strong/></p>\r\n<br/>\r\n\r\n<h3>Creation of the IPS''s cells</h3>\r\n\r\n <p>Since all cells in our body have the same genome, the differentiation process must be related with the environment and not a particular sequence of DNA. The environment can activate or deactivate genes, enabling or not the production of proteins, thus changing cell function. Therefore, it is possible to revert a cell back to the pluripotent stem cell state it was in during the embryogenesis with an epigenetic modification.</p> \r\n<p>Epigenetics can involve many different factors, but during the process to differentiate pluripotent cells in order to create the embryo, transcription factors are dominant. These transcription factors have the function to activate specific genes, enabling ribosomes to read them and synthetize the corresponding proteins. Therefore, it is reasonable to think that introducing the same transcription factors present in the early stages of embryo development into an adult cell could activate the proper genes to revert it back to it’s pluripotent state.</p><br/>\r\n<p>Research and screening studies show that is possible to do so using four transcription factors, OCT4, SOX2, NANOG, and LIN28. These proteins are present in the early stages of embryo development, but not anymore in adult cells. Studies show that after 20 days or division with the presence of these factors, cells are just like they were in the first stages of life, with the same morphology, proliferation, surface antigens and the ability to differentiate.</p>\r\n<p>However, replicating these early development conditions with these transcription factors isn’t that easy. We can’t only add these protein in the cell environment since they must reach the nucleus to become active. Therefore, their coding genes are introduced inside the cell genome so the transcription factors can be produced by the cell itself.</p><br/>\r\n<p>To do so, the corresponding RNA sequences are encapsulated within a virus-like phospholipidic membrane, together with reverse transcriptase and integrase proteins. Once this virus-like structure encounters the cell membrane, they fuse together and the plasmide is released in the cytoplasm. The reverse transcriptase protein can then synthetize the DNA sequence corresponding to the RNA plasmide. Once this DNA sequence in double-stranded, it is integrated in the genome with the help of the integrase protein. The cell then begins production of the four transcription factors and its conversion to the pluripotent state advances with every cellular division. After 20 day, they are indistinguishable from natural pluripotent stem cells.</p>\r\n\r\n    <figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/1.jpg" alt="" title=""/>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n<h3>Application of the IPS'' cells</h3>\r\n\r\n<h4>IPS cells offer various advantages</h4>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>reduced chance of immunorejection</li>\r\n  <li>lower costs and risks of clinical trials</li>\r\n  <li>toxicity prediction of newly discovered drugs</li>\r\n  <li>personalization of treatment</li>\r\n  <li>consistent phenotypes for disease modeling</li>\r\n  <li>iPS cells have limited the ethical issues regarding the destruction of embryos associated with the use of embryonic stem cells </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<br/>\r\n<p>Treating a disease is generally very difficult because of the lack of information concerning its progression, hence the need of creating a model which could help find the main cause and annihilate it. Many animal models, mice for instant, are being used for disease modeling because they are capable of mimicking human cell microenvironment, but there are limitations due to genome uniqueness. IPS cells can be a good alternative because of their advantages and are widely used in therapeutics for disease modeling, regenerative medicine and drug discovery.</p>\r\n\r\n   <figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/2.jpg" alt="" title=""/>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n<br/>\r\n<h4>Regenerative medicine</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>This field deals with repairing injured or degenerated tissues by synthesizing in the lab the same tissue using the patient’s iPS cells in order to restore normal function.  When doing a classic transplant, the donor must not have any disease and his physiological profile has to match with the patient. Even though the conditions are fulfilled, there is still the risk of immunorejection.</p>\r\n<p>The use of iPS cells is a good alternative because the transplanted cells are obtained by repairing the iPS cells generated from some of the patient’s somatic cells. This method has helped treating a number of injuries and degenerative diseases, such as spinal cord injury, liver, heart valve and vessel damage. IPS cells have also been used in ex-vivo blood expansion of some blood components. Thus, the generation of red blood cells is possible and could provide a constant supply for blood transfusions.</p> \r\n\r\n<h4>Application of iPS cells in Fondamental Research</h4>\r\n\r\n<h5>Study of Organs</h5>\r\n<p>Development of iPS cell and their differenciation allowed the creation in vitro of Organoids. They are multicellular tridimensional structures which partially reproduce mechanisms taking place in organs. Scientists use them as models to understand some interactions between cells in the organism, and the reaction of the organ when the environment change.</p>\r\n<p>It has the great advantage that by using iPS cells, we can use a theorical infinite number of cells to experiment. So organoids are easily to do, and their littleness makes vanish the problem of the absorption of nutrients which exists for organs in their entirety. </p>\r\n<p>But with this technique we can''t observe interactions between organs as effects of hormones and the simulation of a full organ isn''t possible. We can''t also reproduce all organs.</p>\r\n<p>Existing Organoids  :\r\nCerebral organoid, Thyroid organoid, Thymic organoid, Instestinal organoid, Testicular organoid, Hepatic organoid, Pancreatic organoid, Gut organoid, Epithelial organoid, Lung organoid, Kidney organoid and Gastruloid (embryonic organoid).</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Model of Diseases</h5>\r\n<p>Genetic diseases exist because of some Dna sequences in the genome of cells in the organism. Now we can take somatic cells of the body (of the skin specifically) of patients (they have the same Dna sequence) and then study more precisely the disease by recreating cells which are affected by this disease. iPS cells modified by the CRISPR method are also used.</p>\r\n<p>IPs cells help to generate very good models, to understand mechanism of the disease and the effect that have some therapeutic molecules on the cells. Indeed, we can test the toxicity of them and if they work effectively. Some studies already exist for the type one diabetes, Huntington''s disease, few muscular dystrophies and more.</p>\r\n<p>The value of these models allows advancements in researches, for instance one laboratory had suceed in the cure of a mutation causing hepatic insufficiency in mice. They cured IPs cells they had obtained then differentiated them as hepatocytes before they were feeding back in mice. The liver stayed functionnal and the cells even regenerate the organ.</p>\r\n\r\n<figure>\r\n    	<img src="images/4.png" width="500" alt="" title="intestinal Organoid"/>\r\n    	<figcaption></figcaption>\r\n	</figure>\r\n\r\n<h3>Replacement of animals for scientific research</h3>\r\n<h4>Why should we replace animals in medical research ?</h4>\r\n<p>This question deserved to be asked because the search in replacement of animals requires money and time from researchers. This question can be reformulated in does the end justify the means ?<p>\r\nFirst of all, a huge majority of human use of animals is for food. Sometimes tests on animals are made to cure the specie tested but is it acceptable to sacrifice a few members of a population to save the majority. There are strict rules and control on the use of animals in research to guarantee their well-being, but what is well-being without freedom. Following a pure Cartesian spirit, we can say that the end justify the means but does the life of a single animal worth less than the healthy of humans ?</p>\r\n<p>There is no scientific answer to this question because the role of science is to describe and explain not judge. Even if we wanted use no more animals, would there be alternatives technologies allowing it ?</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>How do we replace animals scientifically</h4>\r\n\r\n<figure><img src="images/3.png" class="imageflottante" alt="Image flottante" /><figcaption></figcaption>\r\n	</figure><br/>\r\n\r\n<p>Actually, the majority of tests on animals are made to determine if a product is toxic or not. So probably, the best way to replace animals would be to create kind of organs on which we could make tests. It is precisely what have been done by Thomas Hartung team in the Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health.</p>\r\n<br/>\r\n<p>Induced Pluripotent stem cells technology is used to create mini-brains from skin of healthy adult people. But as Thomas Hartung says, cells of people suffering of Alzeimer or Parkinson disease could have also been used. Once we have the skin cells, they are reprogrammed into embryonic stem cells then stimulated to differentiate into brain cells.</p>\r\n<p>They are composed of four types of neurons and two types of support cells : astrocytes and oligodendrocytes. The last one insulate neuron’s axons throughout the creation of myelin, and by doing so allow brains cells to communicate faster. The new mini-brain even showed spontaneous electrophysiological activity.</p><br/>\r\n<p>Theses mini-brains are very small 350 micrometers in diameter, on average the size of the eye of a housefly. Indeed, they are produced by thousands copy, and in a same petri dish, there can be hundreds of them. So it is possible to create mini-brains which can have electrophysiological answers, but are the measures scientifically usable ?</p>\r\n<p>To ensure that, Hartung and his team didn’t creat the best mini-brain but a standardized one. Indeed, brains cells will react the same way no matter from what brain they come from and the results will be comparable.</p><br/>\r\n<p>But is there only good ethical consequences from IPS’s cells, because the ability of theses cells to differentiate into any type of cells pose the problem of cloning and more especially, human cloning.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n    <h3 class="dessous">References</h3>\r\n    <ul>\r\n    	<li>Yu J, Vodyanik M, Smuga-Otto K, et al.,<a href=""> « Induced pluripotent stem cell lines derived from human somatic cells.»</a>, Science 2007;318(5858):1917-1920.</li>\r\n    	<li>Takahashi K, Tanabe K, Ohnuki M, et al. <a href=""> Induction of pluripotent stem cells from adult human fibroblasts by defined factors»</a>. Cell 2007;131(5):861-872.</li>\r\n    	<li><a href="https://www.systembio.com/support/resources/faqs/lenti"> « How Lentivirus Delivery Works»</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4313779/"> « Induced pluripotent stem cells: applications in regenerative medicine, disease modeling, and drug discovery»</a></li>\r\n	<li>Thomas Hartung and Helena T. Hogberg., <a href="http://www.jhsph.edu/news/news-releases/2016/researchers-create-mini-brains-in-lab-to-study-neurological-diseases.html"> «Use of human-derived structure could allow for better research and reduce animal testing»</a>, Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health, February 12, 2016</li>\r\n	<li><a href="http://labiotech.eu/animal-testing-stem-cells/"> «Could Stem Cells eventually replace Animal Testing in Drug Development?»</a></li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n    <br/><br/>', '', '', 'english');

